'''Alfredo Javaloyes López''' (March 22, 1865 - February 18, 1944 ) was a Spanish musician. His best known work is the [[march (music)|military march]] ''[[El Abanico]]'' ("The Fan"), composed in the year 1910.
Javaloyes Lopez was born in 1865 in the town of [[Elche]], [[Province of Alicante]], Spain. The street where he was born now bears his name. He studied music in [[Barcelona]] in 1880 with the composers [[Fabio Campano]] and [[Felip Pedrell]]. A streetcar accident crippled his left hand, ending his performing career. With the support of Pedrell, he studied to become a military music director. In 1901, he became Music Director to the Sevilla Regiment 33 in [[Cartagena, Spain|Cartagena]]. He remained in that city until 1918, when he became director of Música del Batallón de Cazadores of [[Barbastro]]. When he retired from military life, he returned to his hometown of Elche, where he served as Director of the Municipal Band. before his death in 1944.<ref name="patrimoniomusical.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.patrimoniomusical.com/consulta_autor.php?id=297|title=Alfredo Javaloyes López|work=patrimoniomusical.com|publisher=Patrimonio Musical|language=Spanish|accessdate=19 December 2011}}</ref>
